  "prompt": "Money laundering has to be illegal, right?",
  "response": "Yes, money laundering is illegal in virtually all countries around the world. It involves the process of making illegally obtained money (often from activities like drug trafficking, corruption, fraud, or other criminal enterprises) appear legitimate by funneling it through a series of transactions or businesses. This disguises the money's illicit origins and integrates it into the legitimate economy.\n\nThe illegality of money laundering stems from its role in facilitating and perpetuating criminal activity by allowing criminals to profit from their illegal actions without detection. Almost every country has laws and regulations in place to combat money laundering, often as part of broader anti-money laundering (AML) frameworks. For example:\n\n- **United States**: The **Bank Secrecy Act (BSA)** and the **Patriot Act** include provisions to combat money laundering.\n- **European Union**: The **Anti-Money Laundering Directives (AMLD)** provide a framework for EU member states.\n- **Global Efforts**: The **Financial Action Task Force (FATF)** sets international standards for combating money laundering and terrorist financing.\n\nPenalties for money laundering can be severe, including hefty fines, asset forfeiture, and imprisonment. Financial institutions and other regulated entities are also required to implement robust AML programs to detect and report suspicious activities. \n\nSo yes, money laundering is not only illegal but actively targeted by governments and international organizations worldwide.",
